Identification of Signficant SNPs associated with T Cell Receptor Diversity

John Lin
March 07, 2019

DSCI 453 Semester Project Presentation 1

Background Info: Genetic Variation (SNPs) and T Cell Receptors (TCR)

  • Genetic Variation
  • Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms (SNPs)
  • Mutations of single nucleotides
  • May result in different phenotypes
  • Example is SNP rs10757278 with genotypes:
    • AA
    • AG
    • GG (most risk for heart attack)

[1] "Zurich (2019)"
  • Adaptive Immunity
  • Lymphocytes (B Cells and T Cells)
  • Specificity, diversity, and memory
  • TCR repertoire through somatic recombination
  • VDJ region of genomic regions (TCRB) determines CDR3
  • CDR3 historically is major factor in TCR structure
  • Focus is \( \beta \) chain of TCR

[1] "M. (2016)"

The Question

Are there any SNPs (genotype) that are significant predictors for TCR diversity (phenotype)?

If so, are there specific clusters of relevant nucleotide and/or amino acid sequences that we can infer based on associated TCR repertoire?

The Data Set

  • After initial filtering…

    • 15 patients with genotype AND immunoSeq data (n = 15)

      • TCR Diversity Metric is Shannon entropy-based measure of clonality:

      $$ProductiveClonality = 1-\frac{Entropy}{log_2(NumberProductiveUniqueRearrangements)}$$

    • at most…82360 genotypes (SNPs) for each patient (TCRB gene, p = 82360)

    • p >> n, typical of GWAS studies

Data Source

  • Blood samples from patients with chronic kidney disease

    • from MetroHealth Medical Center Main Campus
    • collected March 2016 to July 2017

  • Germline Genetic Data

    • processed by Illumina MultiEthnic Genotyping Array (MEGA) BeadChip
    • BED (binary), BIM, FAM files
    • Additive Codes:
      • 0 is A2/A2
      • 1 is A1/A2
      • 2 is A1/A1

  • Somatic Genetic Data

    • processed by immunoSeq Analyzer by Adaptive Biotechnologies
    • CSV files from immunoSeq Analyzer

Data Set Combined Excerpt

Methodology

Major Steps:

  1. Filter SNPs/patients by missingness
  2. Sex check
  3. Filter by Minor Allele Frequency
  4. Filter deviations from Hardy-Weinberg Equilibrium
  5. Filter by heterozygosity
  6. Relatedness
  7. Account for population stratification
  8. Filter SNPs by appropriate window (50,000 bp +/- CDR3)
  9. Combine phenotype data with genotype data
  10. Multiple Simple Linear Regression (Additive Model)

Some done through plink WGA Toolkit

plink Example:

# Linear Model with TCRB filtering
/storage/software/plink --bfile /storage/mips/MIPS_Updated.2019-02-21/data/MIPS_SexCorrected --pheno ../20190301_tcrEmrPheno.txt --pheno-name Productive.Clonality --chr 7 --from-mb 141.2 --to-kb 142 --assoc --qt-means --linear --make-bed --out $outputFolder/linearTest/MIPS_SexCorrected_Pheno_tcrb_linear

Next Steps

  3. Reprocess data for significant SNPs
